All Implemented Interfaces:
ArrayObject<JsNode>, ObjectLike
public final class JsNodeList<T extends JsNode>
extends DOM2Core.NodeList.Prototype<T>
implements ArrayObject<JsNode>

An opaque class representing JavaScript client-side objects of the global JsClient.NodeList class.

The opaque class defines a read-only, ordered list or an array of JsNode objects. The length property specifies how many nodes are in the list, and the item(Number) method allows you to obtain the node at a specified position in the list. The elements of the list are always valid JsNode objects and they never contain null elements.

Objects of JsNodeList behave like JavaScript arrays, and you can query an element from the list using square-bracket array notation in JavaScript, or using get(int) method in JS applications, instead of calling the item(Number) method. However, you cannot assign new nodes to the array (even if using square brackets in JavaScript).

Note that objects of JsNodeList are live, that is, they are not static snapshots but immediately reflect changes to the document tree.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org

public static final Value.Number.Member length

An opaque static field defining a member that is named by the field name without a qualifying member and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsNodeList object refers to the length of the array specifying the number of nodes in it.

item

public final T item(java.lang.Number index)

Returns the specified element of the array object.

This method is equivalent to get(int). In JavaScript, you can use the square-bracket array notation instead of calling this method.

Parameters:
index - The position (or index) of the desired node in the array object. The index of the first node in the array is 0, and the index of the last node is length minus 1.
Returns:
The node at the specified position in the JsNodeList array object, or null if index is less than zero or greater than or equal to the length of the JsNodeList array object.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
